I am hoping I won&#39;t have to go that route, but I will if the amount of 
spam (spams?) increases to the point that it is hampering legitimate 
communication.  We haven&#39;t had a huge number of postings either although 
I would like to see the level of activity increase.

I would like to have a site where people could practice their Quikscript 
reading and writing.  I believe practice in reading other&#39;s writing is 
crucial for developing fluency.  Previously, I have noticed that the 
level of activity on the bulletin boards such as Ikon was very limited. 
 Not much palaver back and forth ever developed.  Perhaps, we would do 
better to add short poems and prose pieces to the files section on 
Reed_Alphabet for newbies to read.  Uploading these sorts of things 
would also give us an opportunity to critique each other&#39;s writing as I 
doubt many of us are expert Quikscript writers.

I was thinking last night that Shavian has its placement in Unicode now, 
and it would make sense for use to apply for unicode placement for 
Quikscript as well.

I was comparing QS to Shavian the other night with the copy of Androcles 
and the Lion which I recently purchased from Phillip Newton.  I was 
wondering about the possibility of trying to combine the two alphabets 
in a manner that both the Shavian devotees and the Reed_Alphabet 
devotees might be able to agree upon.  It had seemed that this might be 
possible since the two alphabet share many similarities.  However, as I 
perused the Shavian alphabet, it once again struck me why I prefer QS. 
 I know the Shavian devotees decry Reed&#39;s abandonment of some of the 
mirror letters in QS that exist in Shavian because they appreciate the 
structure of using mirror letters for voiced and unvoiced consonants. 
 However, this structure means little to most writers since they are not 
linguists and don&#39;t have a clue whether &quot;t&quot; is voiced or unvoiced.  In 
fact, the question of voiced or unvoiced consonants has nothing to do 
with learning to make and use the symbol for a given phoneme.

I believe that the changes in the alphabet from Shavian to QS, which 
essentially simplied the symbols and provided more connection points, 
thus giving QS its cursive appearance, allow a writer to write more 
fluidly and quickly.  I believe this is exactly the goal Reed was trying 
to achieve after he had seen Shavian in use for a sufficient period of 
time by writers from a number of different countries.

The argument, which I have seen made, that most writing nowadays is on 
computer is belied by the number of pens and pencils and post-it notes 
still being sold.  And children still learn to write with pencils, not 
computers.  I daresay no school system has decided that children can get 
by with just learning keyboard skills.  A related aspect of Shavian 
which I find problematical is that some of the vowel symbols are more 
complicated than they need to be, which makes writin them slower and 
harder than the equivalent QS symbols, which I find cleaner and simpler. 
 Also, my 55 year old eyes have a little trouble distinguishing one 
symbol from another in smaller fonts when I don&#39;t have a pair of 
cheaters handy.  I could go on but don&#39;t have the time presently.  

These and similar thoughts made it questionable in my mind that the two 
alphabets could be successfully reunited.  Shavian devotees will not 
want to give up their familiar letter shapes, and Reed_Alphabet devotees 
will not want to give up theirs.  For instance, how do we decide whether 
the symbols for &quot;th&quot; in Shavian be altered to mean &quot;f&quot; and &quot;v&quot; as they 
are in QS, or should it be the other way round?  I don&#39;t feel it 
practicable to use Shavian for &quot;print&quot; forms and QS for &quot;handwritten&quot; 
forms as someone wrote a few months back.  I believe the difference 
between the symbols of the two alphabets can fairly be called cognitive 
dissonance.  If one is acclimated that a QS &quot;f&quot; represents &quot;f&quot;, it slows 
reading down a great deal, if you have to make the transition to realize 
it is a &quot;th&quot; in Shavian or vice-versa.  This problem was exacerbated by 
Reed&#39;s recycling of some Shavian symbols by remapping them onto 
different phonemes in QS.  Perhaps, I am making too much out of this. 
 Any thoughts?

Paige Gabhart



